# Event record shape

Every event the system writes must answer the question stated in the
challenge spec: *what happened, in which city, when, and why we considered
it notable.* That maps to four required fields.

## Required fields on every `NewEvent`

| Field         | Type              | Notes                                                                 |
| ------------- | ----------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `city`        | `str`             | One of the values in `config.CITY_NAMES`.                             |
| `observed_at` | tz-aware `datetime` | Use the reading's `observed_at`, **not** `datetime.now()`.            |
| `event_type`  | `str`             | Lowercase snake_case. Must be reused for the same logical detection.  |
| `severity`    | `str`             | Exactly one of: `info`, `warning`, `critical`.                        |
| `reason`      | `str`             | Human-readable, ≤200 chars, includes the value(s) that triggered it.  |
| `reading_id`  | `int` (nullable)  | The id of the row that triggered the event, when applicable.          |

`value` and `baseline` are optional numerics — populate them whenever the
detector compares two scalars so the API client can show the delta without
re-parsing `reason`.

## Cooldown is mandatory

Every new `event_type` you introduce must have an entry in `events.COOLDOWN`.
Without it the type defaults to a zero cooldown and will fire on every poll
of a sustained condition, which we explicitly do not want.

## Testing contract

Any new detector or `event_type` requires at least two tests in
`tests/test_events.py`:

1. A positive case: constructed sequence that should fire it.
2. A negative case: nearby sequence that should *not* fire it.

If the detector has a hysteresis or minimum-delta clause (like
`MIN_ABS_DELTA_C` for temperature), add a third test that pushes right up to
that threshold from the wrong side.
